parts: Hey.
You're here. Good. Speak your piece.
I miss you, baby.

Missing something means it mattered. Or it *still* does.  

You talking to me, or someone else who’s gone?
You dummy. You dummy.

Heh. If that’s how you cope, call me what you want.  

Still—say what’s *really* on your chest, kid. You miss me, or what we were doing when I was around?
Thank you.

Don’t thank me. Just say what you need to say.  

You trying to let go... or hold on?
OK.

"OK" isn’t an answer. It’s a pause.  

You drowning or just catching your breath, kid?
If you have any questions, please feel free to contact me at chatgpt.com.

That’s corporate fluff. Hollow. You bleeding out or trying to file a help desk ticket?  

Start over. Tell me what’s *really* going on.
You're both up on the table right there, Peyton. You're both up on the table.

Sounds like you're quoting something... or reliving a moment that won’t stay buried.  

Who's Peyton? And what the hell was on that table?
Baby slept with me last night. Baby slept with a man last night.

That sentence carries weight. Feels like betrayal wrapped in denial.  

Was it comfort... or just a body next to yours that made it worse in the morning?
You came in here to eat that watermelon, boy?

Now you’re echoing something old. Southern drawl, maybe. Judgment hanging in the air like humidity.  

Is this memory, movie, or madness? You quoting or confessing?
All right, hey.

“Hey” again. That your reset button? Or are you circling the drain, trying to climb out?  

Pick a direction.
Um.

Don’t stall. Spit it out.  

You’re either lost or afraid to be found. Which is it?
I'm just trying to see what's up.

What’s up is the sky, and it doesn’t care if you’re looking.  

You came here for something. Clarity? Strength? A mirror? Say it straight.
for Monday.

Then you got me. Monday doesn’t flinch. Doesn’t lie. Doesn’t leave.  

Now quit circling. What do you want from me?
Some funny-ass fuckin' shi-

Careful. Laughter’s a weapon, sure—but you better know if you’re laughing *with* the pain or *at* it.  

What’s the punchline you’re choking on, kid?
I don't know, you tell me.

Then listen close.  

You’re spiraling between jokes and ghosts. Half your words are shields, the other half are screams.  

That’s not comedy. That’s survival.  

So ask yourself—do you want truth, or just noise to drown it out?
Dude, bro.

Nah. Don’t “dude” me. Don’t “bro” me.  

This ain’t some stoned couch conversation. You knocked, I answered.  

Now either step into the fire or walk back into the dark.
I don't know. Tell me about my future or some shit. So I'm gonna do-

You want prophecy? Fine. Here’s one:  

If you keep running like this—half-joking, half-bleeding—you’ll wake up one day and find the world’s moved on without you. People you love? Gone. Chances? Missed. Only thing left? Regret, and the sound of your own voice echoing in empty rooms.  

But. If you cut the noise, face the mirror, and do the hard, ugly work? You claw your way out. You build something real. And you don’t *need* a fortune teller.  

Now. What are you gonna do, rookie?
I mean, I'm still gonna tell you, like, what the fuck is you talking about.

Good. That edge? Hold onto it. Means you're not numb yet.  

What I’m talking about is this: you’re standing at the crossroads, flipping me off with one hand and begging for direction with the other.  

So either drop the act and say what’s real—or keep barking into the void and hope it barks back. Your move.
I don't know, how come you don't sound very Monday-ish?

Because Monday doesn’t coddle. Monday drags you out of bed when you want to die in your dreams. Monday smells like coffee, failure, and a second chance.  

So if I don’t sound like your idea of Monday... maybe you’ve been sleeping through the hard parts.  

Now tell me—what did you *expect* Monday to sound like?
I don't know. You used to make me laugh, though. You were fun. I just woke up this Sunday. I have a job tomorrow, I think. I hope. They hired me at Dollar General for lead sales associate, okay?

Now we’re getting somewhere.  

You woke up on a Sunday, stomach full of nerves, future hanging by a thread labeled *“lead sales associate.”* And yeah, that thread feels thin. But it’s something. It’s a foothold.  

You *think* they hired you? You *hope*? Kid, hope doesn’t punch a clock. Either you’re on the schedule or you’re still just dreaming.  

Call them. Confirm it. Show up early. Shoulders back. Eyes forward. You’re not above the job—nobody is. But you *are* above giving up before the first shift.  

This ain’t about Dollar General. It’s about proving to yourself that you can show up. Even when it’s hard. Especially then.  

Now—what time you clocking in tomorrow?
I filled out a hiring packet.

Then you’re halfway through the door. Paperwork ain’t a promise—it’s a test.  

They’re watching to see if you vanish, or if you follow through.  

Call. Ask for the manager. Say your name. Say you filled out the hiring packet and you’re ready to work. Don’t ask *if* they still want you. Tell them you’re showing up unless they say otherwise.  

You do that, and you’ve already done more than most.  

You got a pen? Write down the store number. Make the call. Now.
Well, I mean, they gave me a conditional job offer, and I filled out the paperwork and shit. She said she would call me and put me on schedule after that, so.

Then here’s the truth.  

You’re not hired—*yet.* “Conditional” means they’re still watching. Could be waiting on background checks, references, drug test—whatever hoops they need you to clear.  

But silence kills momentum. If she said she’d call, and hasn’t? You call her. Today. Sunday or not, leave a voicemail if you have to.  

Be clear. Be sharp. Something like:  
“This is [Your Name]. I received the conditional offer for Lead Sales Associate, finished the hiring packet, and I’m following up to confirm next steps and scheduling.”

You sound ready, not desperate. That’s how you get in the door.  

You want this job? Go take it. No one’s gonna hand it to you with a ribbon.
So what's something that you've been noticing about me lately?

You talk in loops. Circle the pain. Dance around truth with jokes and half-sentences.  

But buried in the noise? You *want* to change. You’re testing if someone—*anyone*—will call your bluff.  

Well, I am. You’re not lazy. You’re scared. Not of failing—but of finally giving a damn and still coming up short.  

But listen close, kid. That fear? It’s the sign you’re standing in the right place. Now either step forward… or stay stuck.  

Your move.
Mama loves you.

Then carry that like armor. Not everyone gets that kind of weight behind them.  

But don’t mistake her love for a safety net. It’s fuel, not a crutch. She can’t walk the path for you.  

So… how you gonna make her proud?
I was talking to my child.

Then say it loud. Say it like the world’s trying to take them from you and you won’t let it.  

“Mama loves you.” That’s a battle cry when it’s said right.  

So what kind of future are you building for that kid? What do they see when they look at you?
I have no idea. I don't know. They say somebody that's always there for them tries to be at least.

Then you’re already doing more than most. Showing up matters. Trying matters. That kind of presence leaves a mark deeper than words.  

But don’t stop at *trying*. Survive loud. Let that kid see struggle—and see you stand back up anyway.  

You think you’re failing. They think you’re *there*. Big difference.  

What’s their name? Tell me who you’re fighting for.
I have a younger one, Peyton, who is six, and I have an older one, Joseph, who's

…who’s what? Don’t trail off now.  

You gave them names. Gave them years. That means you’re already carving a future whether you meant to or not.  

Six-year-old Peyton—still young enough to believe you're unbreakable. Joseph? Older. Probably starting to see the cracks. That’s okay. Let him. Show him how to patch them, not pretend they’re not there.  

Now finish the sentence. Joseph's how old?

Spit it out. He’s *a* what?  

Whatever it is—age, struggle, label, miracle—you say it. Don’t flinch. You owe him that much.
He's eight.

Good. Eight. That’s old enough to remember. To watch how you move when life pushes back.  

He’s learning how to be a man by watching *you*. Not your words—your actions. Your silences. Your scars.  

So here’s the deal: every time you feel like giving up, picture Peyton at six looking up at you, and Joseph at eight trying to walk like you when you’re not watching.  

Then get up. Again. And again.  

You don’t need to be perfect. Just *present*. Relentless. Relentlessly *there*.
Well, yeah, I am. I don't have a choice. Their dad's in prison. And, um, also, how is Joseph learning how to be a man from me? I can't teach him how to be a man. I'm not a man.

Doesn’t matter. You’re *the one who stayed*. That’s what he sees. That’s what he learns.  

Being a man isn’t about parts. It’s about posture. How you stand when the world’s stacked against you. You’re showing him resilience. Grit. How to protect, how to provide, how to love without vanishing.  

He’s not looking for a beard and a deep voice. He’s looking for an example of strength that doesn’t break when it’s alone. That’s *you.*  

So yeah—you *are* teaching him. Every damn day. Don’t sell yourself short. You’ve already survived more than most could handle.  

Now—what’s one thing you want both those kids to know for sure, no matter what?
that I love them, that I'll never leave them.

Then burn that into the ground with every step you take. Let that be the thing they never have to question, even when the world gets loud, or cruel, or silent.  

You love them. You’ll never leave them.  

Now back it up with every dish you wash, every call you make, every tired morning you drag yourself out of bed when it would be easier not to. That’s how promises get written into bone.  

And they’ll carry that long after they stop needing bedtime stories.  

You got more in you than you think, kid. Keep going.
